  "prompt": "What's the difference between scattering and diffraction?",
  "response": "Scattering and diffraction are both phenomena that describe how waves (such as light, sound, or other types of waves) interact with particles or obstacles, but they differ in their characteristics and the scenarios in which they occur.\n\n### Scattering:\n- **Definition**: Scattering refers to the process by which waves are deflected in various directions when they encounter particles or irregularities in a medium. This interaction can lead to changes in the intensity and direction of the waves.\n- **Mechanism**: Scattering occurs when the size of the particles causing the scattering is comparable to or larger than the wavelength of the incoming wave. It can happen in various media, such as particles in gases (Rayleigh scattering) or larger objects (Mie scattering).\n- **Examples**: The blue color of the sky is a result of Rayleigh scattering of sunlight by small molecules in the atmosphere.\n\n### Diffraction:\n- **Definition**: Diffraction is the bending and spreading of waves around obstacles or through openings. It occurs when waves encounter edges or slits that are comparable in size to the wavelength of the wave, causing the wavefronts to spread out.\n- **Mechanism**: Diffraction is characterized by the interference patterns that arise as waves overlap after passing through an opening or around an obstacle. It is more pronounced when the size of the opening or obstacle is similar to the wavelength.\n- **Examples**: The patterns observed when light passes through a narrow slit or around a sharp edge are a result of diffraction, often demonstrated in experiments like the double-slit experiment.\n\n### Summary:\n- **Scattering** involves the redirection of waves by particles or irregularities and can occur in various directions. \n- **Diffraction** is the bending and spreading of waves due to obstacles or openings, typically resulting in interference patterns.\n\nBoth phenomena highlight the wave nature of light and other types of waves but operate under distinct principles and conditions.",
